    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "econ_threshold_2016_v2",
    "description": "Re-probes the economic threshold in the 2016-block retarget regime using corrected code. Sweep10b ran with the old dead v27_economic_pct parameter (econ=0.35/0.50/0.60/0.70 all gave identical 5271/1546 block counts), making those results meaningless. Sweep11 confirmed econ=0.50 \u2192 v26_dominant.\nThe bracket [0.50, 0.70] is still open. This sweep probes econ=0.55 and 0.60 with the fixed code (image_tag-based initial fork + corrected switching model).\nAlso updates economic switching params:\n  - econ_switching_threshold: 0.14 \u2192 0.10 (was never triggering at 14.3% gap)\n  - econ_inertia: 0.17 \u2192 0.05 (was probabilistically blocking the rare crossings)\n\nCascade mechanism (from sweep9 at econ=0.70):\n  - v27 retargets at t\u22488,106s (difficulty 1.0 \u2192 0.497)\n  - Committed v26 pool losses jump 9% \u2192 56%, far above 13.3% tolerance\n  - Cascade completes ~4,000s post-retarget\n  - Run must be \u2265 12,100s to capture full cascade; 13,000s gives margin\n\nResearch question: does econ=0.55 or 0.60 produce a sustained v27 win via the retarget mechanism, or does the narrower initial price gap fail to drive enough pre-retarget pool drift to hit 2016 blocks first?\nRun with:\n  python 3_run_sweep.py \\\n    --input econ_threshold_2016_v2/build_manifest.json \\\n    --namespace sweep-econ-thresh-v2 \\\n    --results-dir econ_threshold_2016_v2/results \\\n    --duration 13000 --retarget-interval 2016 --interval 2\n\nNamespace to create first:\n  kubectl create namespace sweep-econ-thresh-v2\n",
